00:07:36.470 --> 00:07:38.200
So take a look at
App Ads for Games

00:07:38.200 --> 00:07:41.740
to see how you can use powerful
signals from Search, YouTube,

00:07:41.740 --> 00:07:45.340
and the Play Store to find the
best players for your games.

00:07:45.340 --> 00:07:47.170
And then finally,
earlier this year, we

00:07:47.170 --> 00:07:49.210
announced our app
streaming service,

00:07:49.210 --> 00:07:51.712
and that will be described
on Stage 6 later today.

00:07:51.712 --> 00:07:53.920
This is somewhat different
than the instant apps that

00:07:53.920 --> 00:07:55.774
were announced at the keynote.

00:07:55.774 --> 00:07:57.440
They have similar
functions, but they're

00:07:57.440 --> 00:07:59.731
used for different things,
and the app streaming people

00:07:59.731 --> 00:08:01.820
are great for letting
people try out games

00:08:01.820 --> 00:08:04.420
by streaming them online without
actually having to download

00:08:04.420 --> 00:08:07.430
the app onto your device.

00:08:07.430 --> 00:08:10.230
It works pretty much like
videos are streamed on YouTube.

00:08:10.230 --> 00:08:11.884
And it lets a
player try your game

00:08:11.884 --> 00:08:14.050
without having to first
download it, which obviously

00:08:14.050 --> 00:08:16.390
can be a big advantage to
getting them up and running

00:08:16.390 --> 00:08:17.700
quickly.

00:08:17.700 --> 00:08:20.900
OK, so let's think about
how some of those advantages

00:08:20.900 --> 00:08:23.820
can boost your games and
bring them to the next level.

00:08:23.820 --> 00:08:26.600
So here, while you're at I/O,
you'll be learning about some

00:08:26.600 --> 00:08:29.464
of the other tools we have
available to developers.

00:08:29.464 --> 00:08:30.880
And I'm urging you
to really think

00:08:30.880 --> 00:08:33.210
about how you'd combine
them, because as I've

00:08:33.210 --> 00:08:35.909
been saying, if you bring
them together in new ways,

00:08:35.909 --> 00:08:38.740
it can really help you launch
new creative adventures that

00:08:38.740 --> 00:08:41.140
draw on a really diverse
palette and increase

00:08:41.140 --> 00:08:44.590
your chances to both get
noticed and reach new heights.

00:08:44.590 --> 00:08:46.890
So let me give you a
few thought experiments

00:08:46.890 --> 00:08:50.370
to show you the kinds of
things I mean, to get started.

00:08:50.370 --> 00:08:53.337
What if you had a game about
exploring the universe that

00:08:53.337 --> 00:08:55.670
was played by thousands who
were in a single [? shard ?]

00:08:55.670 --> 00:08:56.580
together?

00:08:56.580 --> 00:08:58.550
You'd want to have
complex calculations,

00:08:58.550 --> 00:09:00.990
and that could be done
with Google Cloud Platform.

00:09:00.990 --> 00:09:03.100
But the players could
view it on their phones

00:09:03.100 --> 00:09:05.520
or use our Cast Services
that you can find out

00:09:05.520 --> 00:09:07.900
about here, to Cast it
on through their TVs,

00:09:07.900 --> 00:09:10.110
so that they can actually
see their televisions

00:09:10.110 --> 00:09:13.190
with a starscape and pick
out their next destination

00:09:13.190 --> 00:09:14.960
that way.

00:09:14.960 --> 00:09:16.940
Or you might have
heard-- I'm curious

00:09:16.940 --> 00:09:20.510
how many people have seen
our Chrome experiment game,

00:09:20.510 --> 00:09:21.830
Lightsaber Escape?

00:09:21.830 --> 00:09:23.040
OK, a fair number of you.

00:09:23.040 --> 00:09:23.760
Great.

00:09:23.760 --> 00:09:25.470
I thought that was a
really exciting way

00:09:25.470 --> 00:09:27.220
of showing the advantage
of combining what

00:09:27.220 --> 00:09:31.000
we can do with Chrome with
what you can do with your phone

00:09:31.000 --> 00:09:33.300
to control a lightsaber
on the screen.

00:09:33.300 --> 00:09:36.710
But it uses, as most
phones do, three degrees

00:09:36.710 --> 00:09:38.400
of freedom in orientation.

00:09:38.400 --> 00:09:40.740
Imagine using one of our
Project Tango devices,

00:09:40.740 --> 00:09:42.410
or one of the new
phones that Lenovo

00:09:42.410 --> 00:09:45.070
will be making later this
year, so that as you're

00:09:45.070 --> 00:09:47.450
using your lightsaber
to deflect bolts,

00:09:47.450 --> 00:09:50.450
it's not just seeing
which orientation it's in,

00:09:50.450 --> 00:09:52.740
but you can move it side
to side, up and down,

00:09:52.740 --> 00:09:55.210
and much like they
do in the movies,

00:09:55.210 --> 00:09:59.560
send those blaster bolts
back at the Stormtroopers.

00:09:59.560 --> 00:10:01.450
I think that might open
up a whole new type

00:10:01.450 --> 00:10:04.760
of action-adventure game, where
you're controlling what you're

00:10:04.760 --> 00:10:07.270
seeing on your computer
screen with your phone,

00:10:07.270 --> 00:10:10.210
so that can be a great
interface for you.

00:10:10.210 --> 00:10:12.290
And finally, I'll
suggest TensorFlow, which

00:10:12.290 --> 00:10:14.910
has been getting a lot of news.

00:10:14.910 --> 00:10:17.720
And consider how that
open-source machine-learning

00:10:17.720 --> 00:10:19.820
tool might be used in
conjunction with something

00:10:19.820 --> 00:10:22.640
like Google Earth to create
a new kind of game that

00:10:22.640 --> 00:10:26.410
fused alternate-reality gaming
with massively multiplayer

00:10:26.410 --> 00:10:27.660
games.

00:10:27.660 --> 00:10:31.180
Imagine, for example, that you
have a world-spanning game that

00:10:31.180 --> 00:10:34.670
has procedurally generated
objectives all across Google

00:10:34.670 --> 00:10:37.930
Earth, so that TensorFlow
and machine learning

00:10:37.930 --> 00:10:40.050
can help learn each
player's preferences

00:10:40.050 --> 00:10:42.990
and make objectives that are
local to where they are and yet

00:10:42.990 --> 00:10:45.540
fit into the kind
of world information

00:10:45.540 --> 00:10:47.890
that you can pull in
with our services.

