Thank you.

00:11:28.087 --> 00:11:29.920
BEN FRENKEL: Thank you,
Noah, for the intro.

00:11:29.920 --> 00:11:30.420
Hi.

00:11:30.420 --> 00:11:31.510
I'm Ben Frenkel.

00:11:31.510 --> 00:11:34.500
I'm a Product Manager
on the Play Games team.

00:11:34.500 --> 00:11:37.700
And our mission is
to provide developers

00:11:37.700 --> 00:11:42.270
the tools and services they
need to create great games--

00:11:42.270 --> 00:11:45.040
and make money while
they're doing it too.

00:11:45.040 --> 00:11:47.360
Very important component.

00:11:47.360 --> 00:11:50.520
And we launched Play Game
Services three years ago

00:11:50.520 --> 00:11:54.640
at this event, at I/O, and we
launched with just the basics.

00:11:54.640 --> 00:11:57.050
We had achievements,
we had leaderboards,

00:11:57.050 --> 00:12:02.000
we had a multiplayer stack,
we had a Cloud Save solution.

00:12:02.000 --> 00:12:06.520
And since then, we've become
the fastest-growing game network

00:12:06.520 --> 00:12:07.370
ever.

00:12:07.370 --> 00:12:11.030
Today, hundreds of
millions of users sign

00:12:11.030 --> 00:12:13.670
in to Play Game
Services every month,

00:12:13.670 --> 00:12:19.150
and 50% at the top 500 games
on Play are integrated.

00:12:19.150 --> 00:12:22.180
But since then, since
the initial launch

00:12:22.180 --> 00:12:24.870
and over the years,
the needs of developers

00:12:24.870 --> 00:12:26.980
have substantially evolved.

00:12:26.980 --> 00:12:29.240
And we've had to
evolve along with them.

00:12:29.240 --> 00:12:31.990
And Play Game
Services has expanded

00:12:31.990 --> 00:12:35.400
to include advanced features,
like video recording,

00:12:35.400 --> 00:12:40.000
live operations, and a healthy
dose of predictive analytics.

00:12:43.792 --> 00:12:45.740
And slide-- there we go.

00:12:45.740 --> 00:12:50.440
So before I go into the specific
features and case studies

00:12:50.440 --> 00:12:51.964
that I want to
talk about today, I

00:12:51.964 --> 00:12:54.380
thought it would be useful to
take a step back and provide

00:12:54.380 --> 00:12:56.320
some context for
what we're trying

00:12:56.320 --> 00:13:00.220
to do through the lens of
the game development process.

00:13:00.220 --> 00:13:02.090
So to start up on
the left here--

00:13:02.090 --> 00:13:05.400
and I can barely see things
because of the awkward angle

00:13:05.400 --> 00:13:08.170
here-- but starting
off on the left,

00:13:08.170 --> 00:13:11.790
a typical game will
start off with something

00:13:11.790 --> 00:13:13.540
like a brainstorming session.

00:13:13.540 --> 00:13:15.060
I've heard a lot
of game developers

00:13:15.060 --> 00:13:19.340
have a game jam, where people
vote on whatever concept

00:13:19.340 --> 00:13:20.850
they think is the best.

00:13:20.850 --> 00:13:23.650
For some, maybe,
it's a eureka moment

00:13:23.650 --> 00:13:26.710
they have in the
bathtub-- though

00:13:26.710 --> 00:13:30.150
for me, personally, I
prefer mine in the shower.

00:13:30.150 --> 00:13:34.230
And once you've locked
in on an amazing idea,

00:13:34.230 --> 00:13:37.830
it's time to take it one step
further with a prototype.

00:13:37.830 --> 00:13:40.930
And after you've exhausted
your most expedient testing

00:13:40.930 --> 00:13:45.660
options, like your coworkers,
your friends, your family,

00:13:45.660 --> 00:13:48.000
maybe a distant
cousin somewhere,

00:13:48.000 --> 00:13:52.690
you need to expand your audience
by launching a beta program,

00:13:52.690 --> 00:13:54.630
or soft-launching your game.

00:13:54.630 --> 00:13:57.050
And after iterating
awhile, and you're

00:13:57.050 --> 00:14:00.390
confident your game is awesome,
it has a chance to monetize,

00:14:00.390 --> 00:14:03.090
well, you're ready
to launch and promote

00:14:03.090 --> 00:14:06.260
your game to the public.

00:14:06.260 --> 00:14:07.750
Hooray, right?

00:14:07.750 --> 00:14:11.190
But these days,
launching your game

00:14:11.190 --> 00:14:15.580
is just the start of the
journey for a game developer.

00:14:15.580 --> 00:14:19.110
You need to continue to
invest in acquiring new users,

00:14:19.110 --> 00:14:20.720
and you have to
retain those users

00:14:20.720 --> 00:14:23.270
by keeping your
community engaged,

00:14:23.270 --> 00:14:25.850
tailoring and tuning your
content to different player

00:14:25.850 --> 00:14:28.800
segments, and
running live events.

00:14:28.800 --> 00:14:32.030
Those are all very
important components.

00:14:32.030 --> 00:14:34.410
But today I'm going to
focus on just three things

00:14:34.410 --> 00:14:39.110
that Play, and Play combined
with other Google products,

00:14:39.110 --> 00:14:42.690
are doing to drive game
developers' success.

00:14:42.690 --> 00:14:44.210
First, we're going
to talk about how

00:14:44.210 --> 00:14:48.080
we can help you find the right
users at each stage of the game

00:14:48.080 --> 00:14:49.120
development process.

00:14:49.120 --> 00:14:53.080
Then we'll cover how we can help
you tailor and tune your game

00:14:53.080 --> 00:14:55.340
to different player segments.

00:14:55.340 --> 00:14:58.460
And lastly, we'll talk
about how we can help you

00:14:58.460 --> 00:15:02.080
harness the creativity
and enthusiasm

00:15:02.080 --> 00:15:07.730
of your gaming community to
to deepen player engagement.

00:15:07.730 --> 00:15:10.030
So let's start off
with how Play can

00:15:10.030 --> 00:15:12.510
help you find the right users.

00:15:12.510 --> 00:15:15.800
This is a very important part
for everybody's business.

00:15:15.800 --> 00:15:20.300
So at this year's I/O, we're
introducing the Early Access

00:15:20.300 --> 00:15:22.280
section to the Play Store.

00:15:22.280 --> 00:15:24.430
And as I mentioned
earlier, once you've

00:15:24.430 --> 00:15:26.770
built your initial prototype
and have iterated a bit,

00:15:26.770 --> 00:15:29.710
it's important to get feedback
from the largest audience

00:15:29.710 --> 00:15:32.600
possible before you
launch your game publicly.

00:15:32.600 --> 00:15:36.450
And that's what the Early
Access section is for.

00:15:36.450 --> 00:15:39.240
Early Access will
feature exciting games

00:15:39.240 --> 00:15:43.080
that are still in development,
so that early adopters

00:15:43.080 --> 00:15:48.040
and influencers are able to
discover and try out your game.

00:15:48.040 --> 00:15:50.810
And importantly, it also
gives them an opportunity

00:15:50.810 --> 00:15:53.160
to give you private feedback.

00:15:53.160 --> 00:15:56.970
This is the perfect way to
experiment and fine-tune

00:15:56.970 --> 00:16:01.030
your game before it's finally
released to everybody.

00:16:01.030 --> 00:16:03.180
So when you're finally
ready to launch,

00:16:03.180 --> 00:16:06.030
you'll need to promote
your game and find a way

00:16:06.030 --> 00:16:07.520
to drive installs.

00:16:07.520 --> 00:16:10.400
And for those of you who
are indie developers,

00:16:10.400 --> 00:16:11.900
you'll be excited
to hear that we've

00:16:11.900 --> 00:16:15.650
added a new way to highlight
you and your games in the Indie

00:16:15.650 --> 00:16:18.650
Corner collection
on the Play Store

00:16:18.650 --> 00:16:21.610
that we launched earlier
this year at GDC.

00:16:21.610 --> 00:16:24.260
The Indie Corner is
dedicated to highlighting

00:16:24.260 --> 00:16:27.450
truly amazing and unique
games that users love.

00:16:27.450 --> 00:16:29.180
And here's how
the program works.

00:16:29.180 --> 00:16:32.860
So first, you have
to make a great game.

00:16:32.860 --> 00:16:34.609
It all starts there.

00:16:34.609 --> 00:16:36.150
And then you need
to submit your game

00:16:36.150 --> 00:16:40.170
to participate in the Indie
Corner program at this URL

00:16:40.170 --> 00:16:44.730
that you can see on the
left-hand side of the screen

00:16:44.730 --> 00:16:46.660
there-- I guess
your right, sorry.

00:16:46.660 --> 00:16:47.610
Your right-hand side.

00:16:47.610 --> 00:16:51.840
And it's
g.co/indiecornersubmission.

00:16:51.840 --> 00:16:54.980
And from there, a
panel selects games

00:16:54.980 --> 00:16:58.360
for featuring in the
Indie Corner collection.

00:16:58.360 --> 00:17:00.310
It's simple.

00:17:00.310 --> 00:17:04.970
However, there's more to
the Indie Corner program

00:17:04.970 --> 00:17:08.550
than just the featuring, though
that's obviously a big benefit.

00:17:08.550 --> 00:17:13.800
It also serves as a way for
us to have the opportunity

00:17:13.800 --> 00:17:17.700
to help indie developers
understand and improve

00:17:17.700 --> 00:17:19.380
their game performance.

00:17:19.380 --> 00:17:21.450
And I'll walk you
through an example

00:17:21.450 --> 00:17:25.650
of something we did with a
partner of ours, Springloaded.

00:17:25.650 --> 00:17:27.940
So when we started
working with Springloaded,

00:17:27.940 --> 00:17:32.380
they had just soft-launched
their game, Last Vikings.

00:17:32.380 --> 00:17:36.950
And they gave us an early build,
and we tested it extensively,

00:17:36.950 --> 00:17:39.710
and we wrote up a detailed
analysis of some things they

00:17:39.710 --> 00:17:41.880
could do to improve the
game, how they could best

00:17:41.880 --> 00:17:44.000
integrate Play Game
Services, and some

00:17:44.000 --> 00:17:47.650
tweaks they could make
to improve monetization

00:17:47.650 --> 00:17:50.030
and retention.

00:17:50.030 --> 00:17:54.930
Then Springloaded
implemented every single one

00:17:54.930 --> 00:17:56.707
of our recommendations.

00:17:56.707 --> 00:17:59.290
It was extremely impressive to
see it all come together really

00:17:59.290 --> 00:18:03.480
nicely, and the results for
them have been phenomenal.

00:18:03.480 --> 00:18:08.300
So after they made a few tweaks
here and there to their game,

00:18:08.300 --> 00:18:12.390
they were able to double
average revenue per paying user

00:18:12.390 --> 00:18:14.780
and make huge
improvements to retention.

00:18:14.780 --> 00:18:17.910
They in fact doubled
their day seven retention

00:18:17.910 --> 00:18:20.040
on the back of the work
that we did with them.

00:18:20.040 --> 00:18:23.030
And in James
Bernard's own words,

00:18:23.030 --> 00:18:26.940
the Indie Corner program
has been invaluable to us

00:18:26.940 --> 00:18:29.490
in helping us believe
that as a small indie

00:18:29.490 --> 00:18:34.530
we can actually
make it on our own.

00:18:34.530 --> 00:18:38.690
It has been a transformative
experience for them.

00:18:38.690 --> 00:18:40.560
And hopefully you'll
all be excited to hear,

00:18:40.560 --> 00:18:42.400
tomorrow the Indie
Corner collection

00:18:42.400 --> 00:18:44.080
will be live on the store.

00:18:44.080 --> 00:18:47.550
So don't forget
to check that out.

00:18:47.550 --> 00:18:52.390
So let's say you've-- assume
for a moment that you found

00:18:52.390 --> 00:18:53.570
the right users.

00:18:53.570 --> 00:18:56.320
Now you'll want to keep them
coming back to your game

00:18:56.320 --> 00:19:02.800
by turning it into an ongoing
service you deliver to players.

00:19:02.800 --> 00:19:04.660
A very important
piece of that is

00:19:04.660 --> 00:19:07.920
being able to dynamically tailor
content to different player

00:19:07.920 --> 00:19:09.220
segments.

00:19:09.220 --> 00:19:12.090
And in this case
study, what we'll cover

00:19:12.090 --> 00:19:16.110
is how a developer has
combined the player stats

00:19:16.110 --> 00:19:20.680
API with AdMob's
rewarded ads to increase

00:19:20.680 --> 00:19:27.172
ad revenue while not negatively
impacting in-app purchases.

00:19:27.172 --> 00:19:29.380
Because that was the goal--
the original stated goal,

00:19:29.380 --> 00:19:31.600
and they were able to
successfully do that.

00:19:31.600 --> 00:19:33.200
So let me go through
the story here.

00:19:33.200 --> 00:19:35.680
So developer Invent
Venture integrated

00:19:35.680 --> 00:19:39.310
spend prediction into their
game "Galactic Empire."

00:19:39.310 --> 00:19:41.200
It's a great game.

00:19:41.200 --> 00:19:44.930
They used the spend prediction
to determine whether or not

00:19:44.930 --> 00:19:47.740
to show AdMob rewarded ads.

00:19:47.740 --> 00:19:49.380
And here's how it
works for them.

00:19:49.380 --> 00:19:52.120
If a player is
predicted to spend,

00:19:52.120 --> 00:19:55.030
they don't show the
rewarded ad option.

00:19:55.030 --> 00:19:58.520
If a player is predicted
to spend-- to not spend,

00:19:58.520 --> 00:20:01.880
sorry, they will
see rewarded ads.

00:20:01.880 --> 00:20:03.830
And they implemented
this about a month ago.

00:20:03.830 --> 00:20:05.620
And in the short
time since then,

00:20:05.620 --> 00:20:09.290
they've been able to
increase ads revenue by 10%

00:20:09.290 --> 00:20:14.110
without any negative
impact on in-app purchases.

00:20:14.110 --> 00:20:17.440
In fact, they've seen a
slight increase in them.

00:20:17.440 --> 00:20:20.380
And it's a great case study.

00:20:20.380 --> 00:20:23.170
And every developer,
large or small,

00:20:23.170 --> 00:20:27.590
can go out today and combine
the player stats API and AdMob

00:20:27.590 --> 00:20:32.610
in this way to improve
the success of their game.

00:20:32.610 --> 00:20:34.910
And since we launched the
player stats API last year,

00:20:34.910 --> 00:20:37.480
we've continued to
invest in new predictions

00:20:37.480 --> 00:20:40.350
to make the API
even more powerful.

00:20:40.350 --> 00:20:42.480
And we're excited to
announce the launch

00:20:42.480 --> 00:20:44.650
of two new predictions
in the coming weeks.

00:20:44.650 --> 00:20:46.860
The first is a prediction
of how much someone

00:20:46.860 --> 00:20:49.220
is likely to spend
in the next 28 days,

00:20:49.220 --> 00:20:51.220
and the second is a
prediction of whether or not

00:20:51.220 --> 00:20:53.830
someone is likely to
become a high spender.

00:20:53.830 --> 00:20:56.780
And we couldn't be more
excited to see what

00:20:56.780 --> 00:20:58.660
creative things
you'll end up doing

00:20:58.660 --> 00:21:01.570
with these new predictions.

00:21:01.570 --> 00:21:06.680
So let's turn our attention
to how Google and Play can

00:21:06.680 --> 00:21:10.100
help you harness the
energy and creativity

00:21:10.100 --> 00:21:14.730
of your gaming community to
deepen player engagement.

00:21:14.730 --> 00:21:17.940
And so, one thing that
we've recently launched

00:21:17.940 --> 00:21:20.610
is Play Games gamer
IDs and avatars.

00:21:20.610 --> 00:21:23.370
And these are a great
way for your players

00:21:23.370 --> 00:21:28.300
to create their own gaming
persona and express themselves.

00:21:28.300 --> 00:21:30.040
I mean, most of
the people I know

00:21:30.040 --> 00:21:33.390
don't really want to play
games as their real identity.

00:21:33.390 --> 00:21:36.810
I don't want to be known as Ben
Frankel in all the potentially

00:21:36.810 --> 00:21:39.410
strange games that I play.

00:21:39.410 --> 00:21:44.160
And in fact, I have--
I've used the same ID.

00:21:44.160 --> 00:21:46.560
My secret nerd
name Caldorf here,

00:21:46.560 --> 00:21:50.270
which you can see on the screen,
since I created my Battle.net

00:21:50.270 --> 00:21:56.340
account to play StarCraft a
really, really long time ago.

00:21:56.340 --> 00:21:59.910
I was no longer Ben
Frankel, computer science TA

00:21:59.910 --> 00:22:01.960
and college student.

00:22:01.960 --> 00:22:05.520
I was the zerg-slaying
Caldorf the Conqueror.

00:22:05.520 --> 00:22:10.170
And it was very satisfying
to carry that persona to all

00:22:10.170 --> 00:22:11.660
of my games going forward.

00:22:11.660 --> 00:22:15.090
And with gamer IDs, which we
launched earlier in the year,

00:22:15.090 --> 00:22:19.840
I can in fact take this persona
with me to every game I play.

00:22:19.840 --> 00:22:22.670
And as developers, you can
actually tap into this as well.

00:22:22.670 --> 00:22:28.060
You can find out what a gamer
ID is when somebody signs in.

00:22:28.060 --> 00:22:31.090
So if you have a game where you
have your equivalent of a gamer

00:22:31.090 --> 00:22:34.260
ID or a gamer tag, you can
pre-populate that field

00:22:34.260 --> 00:22:36.670
with the ID that I've chosen.

00:22:36.670 --> 00:22:41.990
And that should speed up the
flow of people into your game.

00:22:41.990 --> 00:22:44.360
So now I want to talk about
how the video recording

00:22:44.360 --> 00:22:47.590
API and YouTube can
help developers amplify

00:22:47.590 --> 00:22:50.030
their community's impact.

00:22:50.030 --> 00:22:52.270
So for a bit of
background, late last year

00:22:52.270 --> 00:22:55.970
we made it possible for users
to record their gameplay

00:22:55.970 --> 00:22:57.850
with the Google Play Games app.

00:22:57.850 --> 00:23:00.290
And after an extended
Early Access program,

00:23:00.290 --> 00:23:04.280
today we are excited to announce
that in the coming weeks

00:23:04.280 --> 00:23:08.490
the video recording API will
be available to all developers,

00:23:08.490 --> 00:23:11.810
so that players can bring up
this video recording experience

00:23:11.810 --> 00:23:14.570
directly from your games.

00:23:14.570 --> 00:23:16.560
In addition, players
will also soon

00:23:16.560 --> 00:23:21.450
have the option to Livestream
their gameplay to YouTube.

00:23:21.450 --> 00:23:24.270
So we've seen a lot of
excitement for video recording

00:23:24.270 --> 00:23:27.110
from the smallest developers,
all to the very largest

00:23:27.110 --> 00:23:28.420
we have on the platform.

00:23:28.420 --> 00:23:32.120
And more than a dozen games
during the EAP program,

00:23:32.120 --> 00:23:35.290
the Early Access program have
already launched an integration

00:23:35.290 --> 00:23:36.670
with the video recording API.

00:23:36.670 --> 00:23:41.360
And they're on the store today,
so you can go check them out.

00:23:41.360 --> 00:23:44.610
But I wanted to walk you through
one particularly powerful,

00:23:44.610 --> 00:23:48.360
exemplary integration of
the video recording API.

00:23:48.360 --> 00:23:51.650
And flaregames has just
such an integration

00:23:51.650 --> 00:23:53.440
in their game, "Dawn of Steel."

00:23:53.440 --> 00:23:55.280
And here is how it works.

00:23:55.280 --> 00:23:59.500
So before you launch a raid and
invade another base and blow

00:23:59.500 --> 00:24:04.580
things up, you come to
this screen on your left.

00:24:04.580 --> 00:24:06.960
So there we go.

00:24:06.960 --> 00:24:10.305
And on this screen you
can see that red button

00:24:10.305 --> 00:24:12.410
that has launch right
in the middle of it.

00:24:12.410 --> 00:24:14.490
And you click that button,
you launch the raid,

00:24:14.490 --> 00:24:15.940
and fun ensues.

00:24:15.940 --> 00:24:18.530
Just to the left of that
red button is a camera icon.

00:24:18.530 --> 00:24:20.310
And if you click
that camera icon,

00:24:20.310 --> 00:24:22.380
it brings up the video
recording overlay.

00:24:22.380 --> 00:24:25.660
And then from that overlay,
you have all the controls

00:24:25.660 --> 00:24:30.050
you need to mute your mic,
turn off and on the forward

00:24:30.050 --> 00:24:33.500
facing camera, as well
as of course start

