00:29:46.450 --> 00:29:50.040
But to truly understand
the phenomenon

00:29:50.040 --> 00:29:55.200
of gaming on YouTube, I want
to share a personal story.

00:29:55.200 --> 00:29:58.970
So spoiler, this is
me and my brother

00:29:58.970 --> 00:30:00.780
when we were little kids.

00:30:00.780 --> 00:30:04.280
And I guess the
socks and the sandals

00:30:04.280 --> 00:30:07.960
show that I was born and
raised in Germany, though.

00:30:07.960 --> 00:30:09.980
Thanks mom and dad.

00:30:09.980 --> 00:30:13.450
Anyhow, my older brother
and I would actually

00:30:13.450 --> 00:30:18.230
spend hours and hours of playing
"Monkey Island" together,

00:30:18.230 --> 00:30:21.330
which is why for me today
it's even a greater honor

00:30:21.330 --> 00:30:23.650
to be speaking
here as Noah is one

00:30:23.650 --> 00:30:26.470
of the co-developers
of my childhood games.

00:30:26.470 --> 00:30:31.740
So in YouTube terms, I'm
fangirling a little bit here.

00:30:31.740 --> 00:30:33.950
We'll take a selfie later.

00:30:33.950 --> 00:30:38.470
So back then, it was usually
me watching my brother play,

00:30:38.470 --> 00:30:41.780
and I was throwing in
comments here and there.

00:30:41.780 --> 00:30:44.330
He wouldn't really pass
on the controller ever.

00:30:44.330 --> 00:30:47.610
But also, to me he was just
the greatest "Monkey Island"

00:30:47.610 --> 00:30:52.390
player in the world, and
also the only one I knew.

00:30:52.390 --> 00:30:55.200
But I was just being
greatly entertained.

00:30:55.200 --> 00:30:58.730
And I kept coming
back into his room

00:30:58.730 --> 00:31:01.640
to watch more and more of
his gameplay on the few games

00:31:01.640 --> 00:31:04.010
that he had bought
with his pocket money.

00:31:04.010 --> 00:31:06.880
So we were, if you
think about it,

00:31:06.880 --> 00:31:11.380
our own little gaming community,
even though quite isolated.

00:31:11.380 --> 00:31:15.430
Now, also on the game
development side,

00:31:15.430 --> 00:31:18.300
the industry back then
was quite isolated.

00:31:18.300 --> 00:31:20.610
So developers and
publishers often

00:31:20.610 --> 00:31:23.710
had no clue what was
going to happen the day

00:31:23.710 --> 00:31:25.570
of the release of their game.

00:31:25.570 --> 00:31:28.940
And players wouldn't
really know what

00:31:28.940 --> 00:31:31.220
they were going to
see until they really

00:31:31.220 --> 00:31:34.580
bought the game, unless they had
maybe read something about it

00:31:34.580 --> 00:31:38.490
in a game specific magazine or
heard about it from friends,

00:31:38.490 --> 00:31:41.330
but that was pretty much it.

00:31:41.330 --> 00:31:45.880
Now the future of gaming as
I had imagined it back then,

00:31:45.880 --> 00:31:50.190
where I could just watch
any game I could think of,

00:31:50.190 --> 00:31:51.936
is already happening today.

00:31:51.936 --> 00:31:54.530
And funnily enough,
I find myself

00:31:54.530 --> 00:31:57.070
working at the very core of it.

00:31:57.070 --> 00:32:01.050
With YouTube, we are surfacing
all of these little gaming

00:32:01.050 --> 00:32:05.210
communities and bring them
together without limitations.

00:32:05.210 --> 00:32:09.460
So you see, while it was really
great watching my brother play,

00:32:09.460 --> 00:32:12.390
I could have never imagine
a world where I could just

00:32:12.390 --> 00:32:15.140
choose between different
types of personalities

00:32:15.140 --> 00:32:17.820
to be entertained
by and seamlessly

00:32:17.820 --> 00:32:21.250
switch between games, and
even get recommendations

00:32:21.250 --> 00:32:24.760
to discover new games
based on my preferences.

00:32:24.760 --> 00:32:28.160
And anyone can do all of
that today on YouTube.

00:32:31.100 --> 00:32:35.380
YouTube has really reshaped
the video game landscape

00:32:35.380 --> 00:32:37.140
over the past decade.

00:32:37.140 --> 00:32:39.110
And to fully
understand how, it's

00:32:39.110 --> 00:32:41.980
important to look at
the incredible amount

00:32:41.980 --> 00:32:44.490
of innovative and
creative talent

00:32:44.490 --> 00:32:47.630
that we have on the
platform, who are often

00:32:47.630 --> 00:32:51.840
at the tip of the spear when it
comes to creating new formats,

00:32:51.840 --> 00:32:54.670
inspiring trends,
and establishing

00:32:54.670 --> 00:32:57.070
audience-building strategies.

00:32:57.070 --> 00:33:01.450
Creativity has gone way
beyond just gameplay.

00:33:01.450 --> 00:33:04.620
So today on YouTube,
you can find everything

00:33:04.620 --> 00:33:08.570
from the most engaging and
entertaining let's play video

00:33:08.570 --> 00:33:12.530
to 360 degrees
animations of games,

00:33:12.530 --> 00:33:15.330
to acapella songs of
your favorite game

00:33:15.330 --> 00:33:20.270
soundtrack to animated
series, to even baking

00:33:20.270 --> 00:33:24.480
videos of your favorite
game character as a muffin.

00:33:24.480 --> 00:33:28.340
So people find themselves
more interested and curious

00:33:28.340 --> 00:33:31.230
about gaming content
than ever before.

00:33:31.230 --> 00:33:36.950
And the community is constantly
diversifying, in which gamers

00:33:36.950 --> 00:33:39.460
are not only players anymore.

00:33:39.460 --> 00:33:42.840
And every month, people
watch billions of hours

00:33:42.840 --> 00:33:46.550
of gaming content on YouTube.

00:33:46.550 --> 00:33:50.360
So gaming on YouTube has grown
so strongly that last year

00:33:50.360 --> 00:33:52.950
in the summer we
took a step further

00:33:52.950 --> 00:33:56.720
and we launched YouTube
Gaming, providing a dedicated

00:33:56.720 --> 00:34:02.100
home for users to get connected
to the games, players,

00:34:02.100 --> 00:34:06.720
and culture that matter to
them with videos, Livestreams,

00:34:06.720 --> 00:34:10.889
and actually the biggest
community of gamers on the web,

00:34:10.889 --> 00:34:12.960
all in one place.

00:34:12.960 --> 00:34:15.320
So if you haven't seen
the YouTube Gaming app,

00:34:15.320 --> 00:34:18.380
I highly encourage you to
download it to your phone.

00:34:18.380 --> 00:34:20.989
Or if you are on
desktop, you can access

00:34:20.989 --> 00:34:22.280
by visiting Gaming.YouTube.com.

00:34:26.176 --> 00:34:29.929
Now gaming videos have
gained a lot of traction

00:34:29.929 --> 00:34:32.429
over the past decade,
to the point where

00:34:32.429 --> 00:34:35.000
YouTubers and their
videos are playing

00:34:35.000 --> 00:34:39.750
a crucial role in the economics
of the gaming industry.

00:34:39.750 --> 00:34:43.969
Creator's videos are one of
the major factors influencing

00:34:43.969 --> 00:34:47.630
which games get more
exposure and find success.

00:34:47.630 --> 00:34:50.100
So we've seen an incredible
amount of movement

00:34:50.100 --> 00:34:52.420
on the developer
and publisher side.

00:34:52.420 --> 00:34:56.370
One example of this is "Surgeon
Simulator," an indie game

00:34:56.370 --> 00:34:58.120
by Bossa Studios.

00:34:58.120 --> 00:35:01.310
Now this is a story
from back in 2013,

00:35:01.310 --> 00:35:04.600
and a thumbnail from
a PewDiePie video.

00:35:04.600 --> 00:35:07.510
PewDiePie is actually
our biggest YouTuber

00:35:07.510 --> 00:35:09.590
on the platform by subscribers.

00:35:09.590 --> 00:35:13.550
He uploads mostly gaming
videos, and to date his channel

00:35:13.550 --> 00:35:17.280
has reached more than
44 million subscribers.

00:35:17.280 --> 00:35:20.840
And to date, he has reached
more than 12 billion views

00:35:20.840 --> 00:35:22.920
on his videos.

00:35:22.920 --> 00:35:25.930
So I reached out to
Felix, PewDiePie,

00:35:25.930 --> 00:35:29.080
to get approval to use this
image in my presentation.

00:35:29.080 --> 00:35:33.280
And his only comment to
it was, oh my god Ina,

00:35:33.280 --> 00:35:35.720
what an ancient image.

00:35:35.720 --> 00:35:39.240
So considering three
years as ancient,

00:35:39.240 --> 00:35:44.218
you get a sense of how fast
the industry is moving here.

00:35:44.218 --> 00:35:47.930
"Surgeon Simulator" is a game
by Bossa Studios, an indie game

00:35:47.930 --> 00:35:49.220
developer in London.

00:35:49.220 --> 00:35:52.660
And so, back in 2013
they uploaded this game

00:35:52.660 --> 00:35:58.220
to their game jam site without
really having any expectations.

00:35:58.220 --> 00:36:01.220
Then Felix, also
known as PewDiePie,

00:36:01.220 --> 00:36:04.500
found the game, loved
it, and he decided

00:36:04.500 --> 00:36:07.400
to make a video about it.

00:36:07.400 --> 00:36:10.420
Shortly after he
uploaded the video,

00:36:10.420 --> 00:36:13.190
the game jam site
crashed, because there

00:36:13.190 --> 00:36:16.690
was an overload of PewDiePie
fans accessing the site

00:36:16.690 --> 00:36:18.230
to download the game.

00:36:18.230 --> 00:36:21.840
And to make things
worse, other YouTubers

00:36:21.840 --> 00:36:25.890
followed and created videos
about "Surgeon Simulator,"

00:36:25.890 --> 00:36:29.620
which really
skyrocketed the game.

00:36:29.620 --> 00:36:32.040
And to put it in
Bossa Studios' words,

00:36:32.040 --> 00:36:35.790
the traction in the
first week was insane.

00:36:35.790 --> 00:36:39.630
This exposure and momentum
has led to "Surgeon Simulator"

00:36:39.630 --> 00:36:43.480
becoming the fastest ever
Greenlit game on Steam.

00:36:43.480 --> 00:36:46.900
And they now find themselves
with an established IP

00:36:46.900 --> 00:36:49.770
that has sold over 3
million units across five

00:36:49.770 --> 00:36:51.250
different platforms.

00:36:51.250 --> 00:36:55.380
Way to go for an indie game.

00:36:55.380 --> 00:36:59.150
And over time, Bossa Studios
has become really involved

00:36:59.150 --> 00:37:02.120
with the YouTube
community, to a point where

00:37:02.120 --> 00:37:05.630
in a later version of their
game, the alien version,

00:37:05.630 --> 00:37:09.000
they named the organs after
some of their biggest YouTube

00:37:09.000 --> 00:37:10.310
supporters.

00:37:10.310 --> 00:37:12.600
I know that's very
flattering, but that's

00:37:12.600 --> 00:37:15.780
kind of just the fun of YouTube.

00:37:15.780 --> 00:37:19.020
Another great example of how
they work with the YouTube

00:37:19.020 --> 00:37:23.250
community is from their game
"I Am Bread." "I Am Bread" is

00:37:23.250 --> 00:37:27.540
a very fun action adventure
simulation game where

00:37:27.540 --> 00:37:30.120
the player is in control
of a slice of bread

00:37:30.120 --> 00:37:34.118
and the ultimate goal is
to get the bread toasted.

00:37:34.118 --> 00:37:37.700
It turns out there was
a bug in the game, which

00:37:37.700 --> 00:37:41.310
made the bread float
around in zero gravity.

00:37:41.310 --> 00:37:44.860
And of course, YouTubers
discovered that bug

00:37:44.860 --> 00:37:47.280
and had a lot of fun with it.

00:37:47.280 --> 00:37:49.940
The YouTube community
actually loved that bug

00:37:49.940 --> 00:37:52.960
so much that there were
hundreds of videos produced

00:37:52.960 --> 00:37:54.670
around the floating bread.

00:37:54.670 --> 00:37:57.540
It really became a thing.

00:37:57.540 --> 00:38:01.150
So instead of fixing
the bug, Bossa Studios

00:38:01.150 --> 00:38:03.860
really heard the community.

00:38:03.860 --> 00:38:06.890
They built the zero
gravity mode into the game

00:38:06.890 --> 00:38:09.250
and released it
as a free update.

00:38:09.250 --> 00:38:11.830
So today, you can
find many, many fun

00:38:11.830 --> 00:38:17.020
let's plays on YouTube
around this space bread.

00:38:17.020 --> 00:38:17.800
So guess what?

00:38:17.800 --> 00:38:21.460
Not only indie game
developers are working

00:38:21.460 --> 00:38:23.380
with the YouTube community.

00:38:23.380 --> 00:38:27.040
GTA is a very popular
game on YouTube.

00:38:27.040 --> 00:38:29.680
YouTubers just love
recording their gameplay,

00:38:29.680 --> 00:38:33.540
and it's an amazing game
to develop storytelling.

00:38:33.540 --> 00:38:35.930
So Rockstar, the
publisher of GTA,

00:38:35.930 --> 00:38:38.610
wanted to further
fuel that creativity

00:38:38.610 --> 00:38:42.800
and enable creators to share
more of their experiences

00:38:42.800 --> 00:38:44.940
in an entirely new way.

00:38:44.940 --> 00:38:51.240
So they integrated the
Rockstar editor into GTA V.

00:38:51.240 --> 00:38:55.610
It's a feature built within the
game that lets players record,

00:38:55.610 --> 00:38:57.770
edit, and ultimately
share highlight

00:38:57.770 --> 00:39:01.290
moments from their gameplay
using different camera angles,

00:39:01.290 --> 00:39:03.770
filters, audio, and so on.

00:39:03.770 --> 00:39:06.440
Players can record
gameplay footage

00:39:06.440 --> 00:39:11.150
with only the press of a
single button within the game.

00:39:11.150 --> 00:39:13.350
There is even a
director mode where

00:39:13.350 --> 00:39:17.190
you can stage your own scenes
and create custom moments.

00:39:17.190 --> 00:39:21.100
Players can choose from
different story mode

00:39:21.100 --> 00:39:21.870
characters.

00:39:21.870 --> 00:39:26.430
They can choose location, time,
day, and even the weather.

00:39:26.430 --> 00:39:29.523
When done editing, they can
export directly to YouTube,

00:39:29.523 --> 00:39:35.170
and we've seen some amazing
results coming through.

00:39:35.170 --> 00:39:39.210
We see more collaboration
between developers, YouTube

00:39:39.210 --> 00:39:42.150
creators, and the
community than ever before,

00:39:42.150 --> 00:39:44.190
and it's very exciting.

00:39:44.190 --> 00:39:47.150
Going back to
PewDiePie, he recently

00:39:47.150 --> 00:39:49.590
released his own
game, "PewDiePie,

00:39:49.590 --> 00:39:52.100
Legend of the Brofist,"
in conjunction

00:39:52.100 --> 00:39:55.530
with Outerminds, a video
game development company.

00:39:55.530 --> 00:39:58.010
Now in the process of
developing the game,

00:39:58.010 --> 00:40:01.380
he constantly worked with
his fans and his community

00:40:01.380 --> 00:40:03.050
and got their input.

00:40:03.050 --> 00:40:06.690
He shared sneak peeks of
levels and walkthroughs,

00:40:06.690 --> 00:40:08.370
and they could
give their feedback

00:40:08.370 --> 00:40:09.930
through YouTube comments.

00:40:09.930 --> 00:40:12.750
They also had a say on
which other YouTubers

00:40:12.750 --> 00:40:15.460
should be included in
the game as characters.

00:40:15.460 --> 00:40:19.700
And the community even voted
on the name of the game.

00:40:19.700 --> 00:40:21.860
The feedback from
the community was so

00:40:21.860 --> 00:40:25.550
mind blowing that the game
became number one in the app

00:40:25.550 --> 00:40:29.260
charts right after launch.

00:40:29.260 --> 00:40:32.150
But we also see
developers taking a stab

00:40:32.150 --> 00:40:34.750
at becoming content
creators themselves,

00:40:34.750 --> 00:40:38.010
and quite successfully so.

00:40:38.010 --> 00:40:41.360
Miniclip, for example,
has done a tremendous job

00:40:41.360 --> 00:40:44.920
on their main official
channel, Agar.io.

00:40:44.920 --> 00:40:47.700
They are not only
collaborating with YouTubers

00:40:47.700 --> 00:40:50.580
and curating community
content, they also

00:40:50.580 --> 00:40:53.370
host regular Livestreams,
bringing in the community

00:40:53.370 --> 00:40:55.810
manager and feature
guest players

00:40:55.810 --> 00:40:57.780
on the official channel.

00:40:57.780 --> 00:41:00.800
So this very inclusive
and very consistent

00:41:00.800 --> 00:41:05.580
content strategy has led to
the Miniclip Agar.io channel

00:41:05.580 --> 00:41:09.430
reach over 1 million subscribers
within only six months

00:41:09.430 --> 00:41:14.050
of launch, which is
quite impressive.

00:41:14.050 --> 00:41:17.930
What's great about producing
your own official content

00:41:17.930 --> 00:41:21.890
is that you can then link
directly from the YouTube watch

00:41:21.890 --> 00:41:26.200
page to your game through
what we call cards.

00:41:26.200 --> 00:41:29.450
Cards are clickable
from any device,

00:41:29.450 --> 00:41:32.300
and can either link to
your official website,

00:41:32.300 --> 00:41:36.040
or in the case of a mobile game
directly to the Google Play

00:41:36.040 --> 00:41:40.690
Store and drive
downloads of the game.

00:41:40.690 --> 00:41:44.080
Additionally, the game
pages on YouTube Gaming

00:41:44.080 --> 00:41:47.400
automatically pull together
all the great content

00:41:47.400 --> 00:41:51.000
that is being produced around
your game into one place.

00:41:51.000 --> 00:41:53.270
So that's actually a
great place for you

00:41:53.270 --> 00:41:56.490
as a developer to discover all
the creative talent out there

00:41:56.490 --> 00:42:00.510
that's already creating videos
and Livestreams around your IP

00:42:00.510 --> 00:42:02.480
and get in touch.

00:42:02.480 --> 00:42:04.650
If you've released
a game, I highly

00:42:04.650 --> 00:42:06.620
recommend you to check
out your own game

00:42:06.620 --> 00:42:08.330
page on YouTube Gaming.

00:42:08.330 --> 00:42:11.290
And I've also included
a link in our--

00:42:11.290 --> 00:42:13.750
into our space for
this session, and Noah

00:42:13.750 --> 00:42:18.070
will explain a little bit
about what that is again,

00:42:18.070 --> 00:42:21.740
on how you can provide us with
information around your game

00:42:21.740 --> 00:42:22.940
for these pages.

00:42:22.940 --> 00:42:25.920
Or you could just Google
provide YouTube with game data

00:42:25.920 --> 00:42:27.260
and you will find that link.

00:42:31.170 --> 00:42:35.850
And speaking of more product
innovations, let's talk mobile.

00:42:35.850 --> 00:42:37.810
Now we've looked
at mobile gaming

00:42:37.810 --> 00:42:42.620
and we just see
skyrocketing growth.

00:42:42.620 --> 00:42:45.190
Looking at those numbers,
it was very clear to us

00:42:45.190 --> 00:42:48.960
that we not only wanted to
make it an awesome experience

00:42:48.960 --> 00:42:51.710
to watch people play
from a mobile phone,

00:42:51.710 --> 00:42:54.260
but also to share your
own mobile gameplay

00:42:54.260 --> 00:42:56.730
and broadcast it to the world.

00:42:56.730 --> 00:43:00.510
Now Ben has already told
you about the amazing stuff

00:43:00.510 --> 00:43:03.600
you can do around
integrations within your game,

00:43:03.600 --> 00:43:07.370
but we want to also be
inclusive of any type of game.

00:43:07.370 --> 00:43:10.060
So part of our update to
the YouTube Gaming app,

00:43:10.060 --> 00:43:14.100
as well as to Google Play
Games, as Ben mentioned earlier,

00:43:14.100 --> 00:43:15.740
was mobile capture.

00:43:15.740 --> 00:43:19.280
Mobile capture on YouTube
Gaming is drop dead simple.

00:43:19.280 --> 00:43:22.210
You can select any
game on your phone,

00:43:22.210 --> 00:43:25.680
and just tap the record
button and start capturing.

00:43:25.680 --> 00:43:30.060
You could choose to add video
of yourself, sound via the mic.

00:43:30.060 --> 00:43:33.220
And adding to the
fun of it, you can

00:43:33.220 --> 00:43:36.600
Livestream all of that gameplay
directly to your channel

00:43:36.600 --> 00:43:38.700
on YouTube already today.

00:43:38.700 --> 00:43:42.780
So really your limit to your
mobile gameplay recording

00:43:42.780 --> 00:43:46.380
is only your
phone's battery now.

00:43:46.380 --> 00:43:48.480
And speaking of
Livestreaming, we're

00:43:48.480 --> 00:43:51.360
building up amazing
features on that front.

00:43:51.360 --> 00:43:54.240
As I said earlier, we
see constant innovation

00:43:54.240 --> 00:43:56.300
around formats on YouTube.

00:43:56.300 --> 00:43:58.160
And more and more
creators are now

00:43:58.160 --> 00:44:00.980
connecting to their
fans real-time through

00:44:00.980 --> 00:44:02.140
Livestreaming.

00:44:02.140 --> 00:44:04.530
Also, developers
and publishers often

00:44:04.530 --> 00:44:06.970
use Livestreams to
make announcements,

00:44:06.970 --> 00:44:10.300
to host tournaments, to
host community streams

00:44:10.300 --> 00:44:12.860
around their launches, and
really engage with their fans

00:44:12.860 --> 00:44:14.440
through live chat.

00:44:14.440 --> 00:44:17.710
Life is becoming an ever
immersive experience.

00:44:17.710 --> 00:44:21.790
And we even recently announced
360 degrees Livestreaming.

00:44:24.380 --> 00:44:28.720
It's a very exciting era to be
in today in the games industry.

00:44:28.720 --> 00:44:30.460
And there are so
many cool products

00:44:30.460 --> 00:44:33.770
available to the people
who love and make games.

